The Ukraine on the way to Europe
"The East is East and the West is West, and they will never find each other," Rudyard Kipling once said.
Ukraine lies certainly in the East, but in the East of Europe.
When the country regained its independence ten years ago, European integration became the dominant goal for many of us.
The way there was, however, not always paved with successes, if it was paved at all.
But the result of the parliamentary elections on March 31 has shown that the Ukrainians are still determined to follow this path.
I am a social democrat and was never a member of the communist party, although I was a successful lawyer during the time of the Soviet Union.
For me, it is beyond question that our "Soviet" heritage is largely responsible for the difficulties Ukraine faces in finding its way to Europe.
After the collapse of the USSR, the country had an inefficient and militarized industry as well as an unprofessional bureaucratic apparatus.
The vast agricultural production areas were effectively crippled by outdated machine parks and the lethargy of the state-run agriculture following the Soviet model.
The rural population sank deep into mud and poverty.
Low wages make life here very difficult, pensions are a joke, and the shadow economy is massive.
But our Soviet heritage does not justify everything.
We completely messed up the reform on our own.
For often we wanted to import tried-and-tested concepts from the West - private property, free market economy, strict observance of human rights, creation of civil society, representative democracy - in weakened form and thought that this would somehow help us preserve socialist elements.
Despite these nostalgic inclinations in politics, the Supreme Council (the parliament of Ukraine) has adopted citizens' rights and criminal law, land, family, and economic rights over the years, which is something akin to a revolution.
The acceptance of Western values in a society that has been disconnected from European history for centuries was certainly painful but has picked up speed, although we do not necessarily see ourselves as a typical Western nation.
We see ourselves as more open, sentimental, friendly, and family-conscious, but also more chaotic and apathetic, sometimes irresponsible and lazy.
Still, we are Europeans.
This is seen on the streets and squares of Kiev.
Today, car drivers let pedestrians cross the street, just like in Geneva or Munich (while pedestrians in Moscow still have to protect themselves from reckless drivers).
In Kiev, there is now a lively café scene and friendly public squares where people can stop and enjoy life.
The young people learn English, German, and French, they can use computers and surf the Internet in the Internet cafes.
But these are only the sentimental digressions of someone who loves Kiev very much.
The sober view of a professional politician, which I am, sees deeper-seated changes.
In the last ten years, a development from total rejection of reforms to a policy of half-hearted reforms from corrupt motives to a gradual introduction of Western practices has taken place.
The administrative reform reflects this very vividly.
At first, the reform of the state evoked hostile feelings both among bureaucrats and among ordinary citizens.
A drastic and unconsidered reduction of civil servants in the public service began.
It was a "ready-to-use" reform: the state must shrink, one thought, and then the government would run smoothly.
Niemand dachte darüber nach, dass es Länder wie Frankreich oder die Schweiz irgendwie schaffen, mit großen Staatsapparaten zu gedeihen.
Denn das Problem ist nicht nur ein Problem der Größe, sondern auch der Organisation und Zweckmäßigkeit.
The Erkenntnis, dass die Regierung nicht unbedingt dadurch besser wird, dass man den Rotstift ansetzt, führte uns zum zweiten Stadium in unserem Reformprozess.
Langsam wurde der Staat auf überlegtere Weise reformiert.
Man richtete neue Abteilungen und Posten für Staatssekretäre mit einem klar definierten Aufgabengebiet ein.
By doing so, the work of the government ministries was stabilized.
At the beginning, the power transferred to these new areas was a bit too far-reaching to make their work more effective.
Now they are functioning more or less normally.
Ukrainians may perhaps get annoyed with these impersonal modern mechanisms sometimes, but they increasingly accept them as necessary (if only reluctantly).
Reasonable politicians also accept them.
Only radicals and populists - of which we still have too many - can afford to take a neutral stance towards a more efficient state.
Taming our radicals and the radical impulse was not easy.
Why?
The Ukraine was too long a province of the USSR and the tsarist empire, the most important but nonetheless a province.
This has shaped our mentality. For radicalism is a byproduct of provincial inferiority complexes.
An overwhelming feeling of inferiority and our efforts to deny it have led to the most scandalous moments in Ukrainian politics.
The provincial can by no means admit his own inferiority and refuses to learn from others.
In the measure in which we strip ourselves of our provincial impulse to defend ourselves, we open ourselves up to the best of what others can offer us.
A century ago, the Ottoman Empire was ridiculed as "the sick man of Europe."
Since 1991, the Ukrainians had to recognize that their country had inherited this sad title in the eyes of many Europeans.
In the course of a decade, we may have even contributed to becoming even more frail, but the recently held elections, which brought the communists to their dominant position in the Supreme Council and significantly reduced the power of the "mighty parties" around President Kuchma, have pushed our provincial radicals to the margins of politics.
The reform parties and European parties have won.
As European outsiders or at least as a people on the periphery of Europe, we want to establish a society in which there are no outsiders or people on the periphery.
As the great and at the time already American writer Vladimir Nabokov said in the 1970s: "Of all the achievements of nature, the most astonishing is probably the survival of the weakest."
The long, arduous path to Europe has helped a weak new nation to become strong and to survive.
